cEcENAME cEcA


|global-mode
    global-mode - Change a global buffer mode
|add-global-mode
    add-global-mode - Set a global buffer mode
|delete-global-mode
    delete-global-mode - Remove a global buffer mode
$a


cESYNOPSIS cA


    cCncA cDglobal-modecA "cCmodecA" (cDesc mcA)  
    cDadd-global-modecA "cCmodecA"  
    cDdelete-global-modecA "cCmodecA"  


cEDESCRIPTION cA


    cDglobal-modecA changes the state of one of the hereditary global modes. A
    buffer's modes are initialized to the global modes when first created.
    This command is very useful in changing some of the default behavior such
    as case sensitive searching (see the example below). See lsOperating ModeslmOperating Modesle
    for a full list and description of modes. Also see lsbuffer-mode(2)lmbuffer-mode(2)le for a
    full description of the use of the argument cCncA.

    The lsabout(2)lmabout(2)le command gives a list of the current global and buffer modes.

    cDadd-global-modecA and cDdelete-global-modecA are macros defined in meme3_8.emf
    which use global-mode to add or remove a global mode. They are defined for
    backward compatibility with MicroEMACS v3.8 and for ease of use; they are
    simple macros, add-global-mode is defined as follows:

sB
          define-macro add-global-mode
              ; Has the require mode been given as an argument, if so add it
              !force 1 global-mode @1
              !if &not $status
                  ; No - use 1 global-mode to add a mode
                  !nma 1 global-mode
              !endif
          !emacro

sA
cEEXAMPLE cA


    The following example globally disables lsexact(2m)lmexact(2m)le and lsmagic(2m)lmmagic(2m)le modes, if
    these lines are copied to the user setup file then are searches will be
    simple and case insensitive by default:

sB
          -1 global-mode "exact"
          -1 global-mode "magic"

sA
cENOTES cA


    Globally adding lsbinary(2m)lmbinary(2m)le, lscrypt(2m)lmcrypt(2m)le and lsrbin(2m)lmrbin(2m)le modes is strongly
    discouraged as any file loaded would be assigned these modes. Instead use
    the numeric argument of command lsfind-file(2)lmfind-file(2)le or commands lsfind-bfile(3)lmfind-bfile(3)le and
    lsfind-cfile(3)lmfind-cfile(3)le.

    lsauto(2m)lmauto(2m)le, lsautosv(2m)lmautosv(2m)le, lsbackup(2m)lmbackup(2m)le, lsexact(2m)lmexact(2m)le, lsmagic(2m)lmmagic(2m)le, ls$quiet(5)lmquiet(5)le, lstab(2m)lmtab(2m)le
    and lsundo(2m)lmundo(2m)le modes are present on all platforms by default. On Windows and
    DOS platforms lscr(2m)lmcr(2m)le and lslf(2m)lmlf(2m)le is also present and on DOS lsctrlz(2m)lmctrlz(2m)le is
    also present.


cESEE ALSO cA


    lsOperating ModeslmOperating Modesle, lsbuffer-mode(2)lmbuffer-mode(2)le, lsfind-bfile(3)lmfind-bfile(3)le, lsfind-cfile(3)lmfind-cfile(3)le, lsabout(2)lmabout(2)le.
