! 3 encase
cEcENAME cEcA


    encase - Encase a text region with start/end string
$a


cESYNOPSIS cA


|encase
    cDencasecA "cCstart-stringcA" "cCend-stringcA"


cEDESCRIPTION cA


    cDencasecA provides a short cut to encapsulate a selected region of text with
    a cCstart-stringcA and cCend-stringcA pattern. The command is modal and operates
    in two different operating modes as follows.

    First run cDencasecA without a current region section (i.e. no selected
    highlighted text) and the user is prompted for the cCstart-stringcA and
    cCend-stringcA. The user is also prompted if the command has not been run
    before and the cCstart-stringcA and cCend-stringcA are undefined.

    With the strings defined then select a region with the mouse or keyboard
    (cDesc spacecA and cDmovecA or cDS-movecA) to define the start and end point of the
    region. With a selected region then execute the cDencasecA command using cDesc xcA
    cDencasecA. This is most effective when bound to a simple key, see
    lsglobal-bind-key(2)lmglobal-bind-key(2)le.


cENOTES cA


    cDencasecA is a macro defined in cGmisc.emfcA.


cESEE ALSO cA


    lsglobal-bind-key(2)lmglobal-bind-key(2)le.
! 3 number-items
cEcENAME cEcA


    number-items - Renumber a vertical list of items
$a


cESYNOPSIS cA


|number-items
    cDnumber-itemscA cCstart-numbercC cAchar-widthcC cAnum-linescA


cEDESCRIPTION cA


    cDnumber-itemscA provides a short cut method of re-numbering a list of
    vertically aligned numbered items. The command assumes a fixed width
    number per line. The command operates from the current cursor position in
    a downward direction. The parameters are defined as follows:

    cCstart-numbercA
    
       The value of the first item to renumber.

    cCchar-widthcA
    
       The width of the number space i.e. 1-10 is a width of 2, 89-101 is a
       width of 3.

    cCnum-linescA
    
       The number of lines to re-number, including the current line.


cEEXAMPLE cA


    The following code fragment shows how a list is renumbered.

        MY_COMMAND (myCMD_UP,   # 9, "Move Up")
        MY_COMMAND (myCMD_DOWN,  10, "Move down")
        MY_COMMAND (myCMD_LEFT,  15, "Move down")
        MY_COMMAND (myCMD_RIGHT, 10, "Move down")


    To to use the command to renumber the list from 100 to 103 then the cursor
    is placed at the left hand side where the number should start. In the
    example this is cG#cA, then issue the command cDesc xcA cDnumber-itemscA cD100cA cD3cA cD4cA. This
    renumbers the list resulting in the following:

        MY_COMMAND (myCMD_UP,   100, "Move Up")
        MY_COMMAND (myCMD_DOWN, 101, "Move down")
        MY_COMMAND (myCMD_LEFT, 102, "Move down")
        MY_COMMAND (myCMD_RIGHT,103, "Move down")


cENOTES cA


    cDnumber-itemscA is a macro defined in cGmisc.emfcA.


cESEE ALSO cA

! 3 jeany-bindings
! 3 jeany-osd
! 3 jeany-osd-undo
cEcENAME cEcA


    jeany-bindings    - creates Geany like bindings with a C-j prefix
    jeany-osd         - creates menu entries for the new jeany bindings
    jeany-osd-undo    - restores the original MicroEmacs menu entries again
$a


cESYNOPSIS cA


    cDjeany-bindingscA  
    cDjeany-osdcA  
    cDjeany-osd-undocA

cEDESCRIPTION cA

    The command cDjeany-bindingscA installs key-bindings similar to the bindings
    you find in the Geany text editor but with a 'C-j' prefix. Such key-bindings
    are probably  more  similar to that what new users  expect.  To  not  break
    the original Emacs  key-bindings all Geany key-bindings are prefixed with the
    cCCtrl-jcA  key. The menu  entries can be as well  adapted to show the changed
    key-bindings using the command cDjeany-osdcA, these changed menu entries can
    be reverted to the normal key bindings using the command cDjeany-osd-undocA.
    The  following  key-bindings  are  currently  available  if you  execute the
    command cDjeany-bindingscA:
    
    
    cDFile menu commands:cA

    - cCCtrl-j C-ncA - find-file (creates a new file if it does not yet exists)
    - cCCtrl-j C-ocA - find-file (open a file)
    - cCCtrl-j C-wcA - delete-buffer (close it)
    - cCCtrl-j C-scA - save-buffer
    - cCCtrl-j C-rcA - reread-file (refresh the buffer if it has been modified)
    - cCCtrl-j C-pcA - print-buffer
    - cCCtrl-j C-qcA - exit-emacs 
    
    cDEdit menu commands:cA
    
    - cCCtrl-j Ctrl-zcA - undo (undo editing possible until last save)
    - cCCtrl-j Ctrl-xcA - kill-region (cut marked text)
    - cCCtrl-j Ctrl-ccA - copy-region (copy marked text)
    - cCCtrl-j Ctrl-vcA - yank (paste text)
    - cCCtrl-j VcA      - reyank (paste previous copied text(s))
    - cCCtrl-j Ctrl-acA - jeany-select-all (mark all text)
    
    cDSearch menu commands:cA
 
    - cCCtrl-j Ctrl-fcA - isearch-forward (search forward)
    - cCCtrl-j Ctrl-gcA - hunt-forward (search again)
    - cCCtrl-j GcA      - hunt-backward (repeat search backward)
    - cCCtrl-j Ctrl-lcA - goto-line
    
    cDFont size commands:cA
    
    - cCCtrl-j Ctrl-+cA - increase font-size
    - cCCtrl-j Ctrl--cA - decrease font-size
     

cEEXAMPLE cA


sB
    jeany-bindings
    jeany-osd
sA
cENOTES cA


    cDjeany-bindingscA  and the osd macros cDjeany-osdcA and cDjeany-osd-undocA 
    are macros  defined in  cGjeany.emfcA.  The osd macros are only  available  if
    cDjeany-bindingscA was called before by the user.
    
    In case you have trouble using  Ctrl-Space to start your text  selection you
    can, for a more conventional  region selection use i the user-setup the
    "Start-Up" option "MS Shift region" to begin your text selection.


cESEE ALSO cA

    For    other    more     invasive     changes    of     key-bindings     see
    lsuser-setup(3)lmuser-setup(3)le  where  the  selection  of  completely  other
    key-bindings is explained.

