cESYNOPSIS cA

    cCncA cDtcl-execcA  
    cDtcl-formatcA  
    cDtcl-lintcA       
    set-variable cC%tcl-format-optscA "cCstringcA"    
    set-variable cC%tcl-lint-optscA "cCstringcA"  
    set-variable cC%tclsh-comcA "cCstringcA"  
     
cEDESCRIPTION cA
     
    The cDtcl-formatcA macro formats the currently edited file using one the
    Tcl formatter cGtclfmtcA which is a Python script which you can install usually
     using the pip3 package manager with `pip3 install tclint --user`. This package
    contains  the command  line  applications  cGtclintcA and cGtclfmtcA. To set the
    options  for  the  formatter,  you can  change  the  value  of the  variable
    cC%tcl-format-optscA  for instance like this: 
    
          set-variable %tcl-format-opts "tclfmt --spaces-in-braces %s"

    The cDtcl-lintcA macro checks the currently edited file using the Python
    package  tool cGtclintcA  which must be installed by the user using the Python
    package manager  pip like  this: 

          pip3 install tclint --user

    After executing the macro cDtcl-lintcA a popup-window (cG*tcl-lint*cA) displays the
    warning messages of the cGtclintcA program, the user can click on the hilighted 
    lines showing warnings and jump directly to the problematic line. The same
    can be achieved by pressing th ENTER key on the highlighted line using
    the keyboard navigating to the warning or error line and pressing the ENTER key.

    Setting the variable cC%tcl-lint-optscA allows you to customize the linter
    settings.

    The cDtcl-execcA macro executed the currently edited file using the tclsh
    command line interpreter. Before the script is executed lssave-some-buffers(2)lmsave-some-buffersle
    is executed to allow the user to ensure that all relevant buffers are saved.
    If bit  cG0x01cA  of the  numeric  argument  cCncA is  clear  then all  modified
    buffers are automatically saved, when set (the default) the user is prompted for
    each  buffer. If bit cG0x02cA of the numeric  argument is clear (the  default)
    the user is prompted for any additional  cCcommand-line-argumentscA  which are
    passed to the Tcl command. The arguments given are stored in a buffer variable,
    cD:tcl-exec-argscA, and used as the default arguments next time the script is executed.
    
    After  executing the script, a cG*tcl-exec*cA  buffer is opened with the output
    of the script execution.If any numeric argument is given before calling
    the script, then the user is asked for command line arguments which should
    be given on the message line.

    After executing the macro a popup-window (cG*tcl-exec*cA) displays the results
    of the script  execution. The user can click on the hilighted  lines showing
    warnings and errors and jump directly to the problematic  line in the source
    script.  The  same  can  be  achieved  by  pressing  the  ENTER  key  on the
    highlighted line using the keyboard.

cEEXAMPLES cA

sB
       tcl-format              ; formats the current Tcl file using tclfmt
       set-variable %tcl-format-opts "tclfmt --spaces-in-braces %s"
sA
    Here an example to lint the currently edited Tcl script.

sB
      ; by modifying the macro variable %tcl-lint-opts
      ; you can add no  standard options to tclint like here
      set-variable %tcl-lint-opts "tclint  --style-line-length 120 %s"
      ; during editing a Tcl file press Esc x and then execute
      tcl-lint
