! 5 $file-ignore
cEcENAME cEcA


    $file-ignore - File extensions to ignore
$a


cESYNOPSIS cA


    cD$file-ignorecA "cCstringcA"; Default is ""


cEDESCRIPTION cA


    cD$file-ignorecA specifies a space separated list of file endings which the
    file completion is to ignore. This is used by any function which prompts
    the user for a file name, such as lsfind-file(2)lmfind-file(2)le. A file ending in this case
    is NOT the extension but the last cCncA characters where cCncA is the number of
    characters in the specified ignore file.


cEEXAMPLE cA


    To ignore all files which have the extension cGcGocAcA, using:

sB
          set-variable $file-ignore "o"

sA
    would not only ignore cGcGfoo.ocAcA, but also cGcGfoo.oocAcA, cGcGfoo.pocAcA and cGcGfoocAcA as
    well as any file that ends in an cGcGocAcA. What is really required is

sB
          set-variable $file-ignore ".o"

sA
    It is useful to ignore the cGcG./cAcA and cGcG../cAcA directories so that a directory
    containing one file will auto-complete to that one file. This is achieved
    by using:

sB
          set-variable $file-ignore "./"

sA 
    To ignore MicroEmacs 2009 backup files (cGcG~cAcA), C object files (cGcG.ocAcA), cGcG./cAcA
    and cGcG../cAcA directories try using:

sB
          set-variable $file-ignore "~ .o ./"

sA
cENOTES cA


    The file completion only completes further than the first non-unique point
    in the current list of possibles if and only if it can ignore all but one
    file, so if the current directory contains:

         ./ ../ foo foo.c foo.c~ foo.o


    using the above ignore list, completing with "" has no effect as cGcGfoocAcA and
    cGcGfoo.ccAcA cannot be ignored; completing with cGcGfoo.cAcA will however complete to
    cGcGfoo.ccAcA.


cESEE ALSO cA


    lsfind-file(2)lmfind-file(2)le.
! 5 $show-region
cEcENAME cEcA


    $show-region - Enable the hilighting of regions
$a


cESYNOPSIS cA


    cD$show-regioncA cCflagcA; Default is cG1cA


cEDESCRIPTION cA


    cD$show-regioncA enables or disables the current region hilighting, normally
    associated with mouse interaction in a buffer. Region hilighting occurs
    between the cCmarkcA (see lsset-mark(2)lmset-mark(2)le) and cCpointcA (current cursor) positions
    within the current buffer. An argument cCncA of 0 disables region hilighting,
