cEcESYNOPSIS cEcA


    python - Python Language File.


cEFILES cA


    cDhkpython.emfcA - Python language file hook definition  
    cDpython.eafcA   - Python abbreviation file   
    cDpython.etfcA   - Python template file   

cEEXTENSIONS cA


    cD.pycA - Python file


cEMAGIC STRINGS cA


    cD^#![ \t]*/.*env[ \t]+pythoncA
    
       MicroEmacs 2009 recognizes the magic string on the first line of the
       file used to locate the executable. The Python files may be
       extension-less and are still recognized.


cEDESCRIPTION cA


    The cDpythoncA file type template provides simple hilighting of Python files,
    the template provides minimal hilighting.

    File recognition is performed using the standard file extension cD.pycA, or by
    the magic string.

    The Python file hook offers as well folding and support for displaying an outline
    of the functions and classes of the Python script for easy navigation using the 
    lsitem-list(3)lmitem-list(3)le  command and expanding abbreviations either via short strings using
    the lsexpand-abbrev-handle(3)lmexpand-abbrev-handle(3)le command and visually  inserting abbreviations using the
    lsabbrev-list(3)lmabbrev-list(3)le macro.

    cDFolding and Information HidingcA
    
       Generic folding is enabled within the Python files. The folds occur about the
       cDdefcA or  cDclasscA  keywords  located on the   left-hand  margin.  The following
       commands are supported to show and hide  the function bodies. 
       
       lscollapse-all(3)lmcollapse-all(3)le     -  (un)folds all regions in the file,  
       lscollapse-current(3)lmcollapse-current(3)le - (un)folds the current region.

    cDList ItemscA

       Item listing is available and the key constructs of the file may be listed
       using  the lsitem-list(3)lmitem-list(3)le command.

    cDAbreviationscA

       The installation comes with a default abbreviation file for Python editing
       which can be used by writing short abbreviations like "cCforcA", "cCifcA" or "cCdefcA" - 
       for Python functions. More extended abbreviations are "cCmaincA" for an Python
       application outline or "cCclasscA" for a Python class template. The short strings
       are then replaced by pressing the key-binding for the lsexpand-abbrev-handle(3)lmexpand-abbrev-handle(3)le
       command. The list of abbreviations can be used as well interactively in the GUI
       version of MicroEmacs using the  lsabbrev-list(3)lmabbrev-list(3)le command.

    cDShort CutscA
          
       The short cut keys used within the buffer are:-

       cDC-c C-ccA - Comment out the current line.  
       cDC-c C-dcA - Uncomment the current line.  
       cDC-c C-ecA - Comment to the end of the line with stars (*).  
       cDA-C-icA   - Restyle the current region.  
       cDesc qcA   - Format a comment.  
       cDesc ocA   - Format a comment.  
       cDf2cA      - (un)fold the current region  
       cDf3cA      - (un)fold all regions
       cDf6cA      - show the item-list outline
       cDEsc f6cA  - hide the item-list outline

    cDExecuting, Formatting and LintingcA
    
      cD%fhook-python-execcA - The command to execute the current Python file, default on Unix systems
        is set to cC"python3 %f"cA where cC%fcA represents the file name of the current script.
              
      cD%fhook-python-formatcA - The command to format current Python file, default is set to
       cC"ruff format %f"cA  or cC"yapf -i %f"cA or cC"black -q %f"cA if one of these tools is available, 
       where again cC%fcA represents the file name.
       If you have installed them as Python packages, you should this variable to cC"python -m ruff"cA
       for instance.
              
      cD%fhook-python-lintcA - The command to check/lint the current Python file, default is set to 
       cC"ruff check %f"cA  or cC"pylint %f"cA if one of these tools is available cC%fcA represents the file name.
       If you have installed them as Python packages, you should this variable to cC"python -m pylint"cA
       for instance.
    
      The setting assume that the cCpython3cA, the cCruffcA or the cCyapfcA programs are available
      via the cCPATHcA environment variable. On Windows you must insert here either the complete
      file path to the executables or add the folder where this file is to the cCPATHcA variable.

      These global variables should be changed if necessary usually within your cCUSERNAME.emfcA 
      or the cCmypython.emfcA file. Here an example to use ruff as Python package based on a local
      install of Python into a virtual environment.
      
sB
          set-variable %fhook-python-exec "/home/username/venv/bin/python3 %f"
          set-variable %fhook-python-lint "/home/username/venv/bin/python3 -m ruff check %f"
          set-variable %fhook-python-format "/home/username/venv/bin/python3 -m ruff format %f"
sA
cEBUGS cA


    There would appear to be too much applied hilighting in this file, it
    could probably do with rationalizing.


